    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-02-11T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-02-11T17:00:00-05:00" n="293"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d293">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.60/2–1147: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to General
                        of the Army <persName type="to">Douglas MacArthur</persName>, at Tokyo</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-02-11T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 11, 1947—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>43. Personal for MacArthur from George Atcheson.<note n="30" xml:id="d293fn30"
                        >The Political Adviser in Japan was in Washington for consultation.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item> Yesterday American Delegation <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> invited
                        me to sit with them preparatory to full <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>
                        meeting Feb 13. Principal topic was paper on retention Jap industrial
                        plants. Delegation fully realizes importance of getting this paper through
                            <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> soonest and has been making <pb
                            facs="0367" n="353" xml:id="pg_353"/> strenuous efforts to do so. Matter
                        has now come to point where Soviet member is agreeable, providing
                        authorization to you to undertake retention of plants contains some
                        reference to consultation with Allied Council. Specific Soviet proposal is
                        to use words “after consultation with Allied Council”. One alternate
                        American suggestion was “after such consultation as may be called for under
                        the Council’s terms of reference”.</item>
                    <label/>
                    <item>My views were requested and I pointed out strong objections to any
                        reference to consultation with Council on various grounds as such reference
                        would open way for Derevyanko to demand some system of plant inspection with
                        his staff participating and also as non-compliance with recommendation of
                        Council would expose <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> to public Soviet
                        and possibly other criticism as well as providing Soviet press with further
                        anti-American propaganda material. However, in the light of importance of
                        achieving early <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> approval of the paper,
                        American delegation still feels it will have to make some language
                        concession to Soviet along the lines of that suggested. While this will
                        undoubtedly bring about difficulties envisaged there will be no impairment
                        of your authority and it might be possible to handle matter with a minimum
                        of trouble by asking Council members by letter for their recommendations and
                        at the same time exercising your full authority by going forward with the
                        program.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Other subject was publication of Constitutional review decision. My views
                        and delegation’s were as widely divergent as before and discussion was
                        inconclusive.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
